vely. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n189,\"\"\"VARIABLE COSTS\"\"\",\"Variable Costs are expenses that vary directly with the level of production or sales. These costs include direct materials, direct labor, and other expenses such as machine set-up costs. They are relevant in decision-making as they will change with the decision to increase or decrease production. For example, in the production of keypads and display screens, variable costs encompass raw materials and direct labor. In Division B, variable costs include $13 for adaptors, $45 for other materials, and $35 for labor per battery, while in Division A, they include $3 for materials and $4 for labor per adaptor. Variable costs increase as production increases and decrease as production decreases, making them a crucial consideration in marginal costing and overall financial planning.\",9\n412,\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION MARGIN\"\"\",Contribution margin is the difference between sales revenue and variable costs. It is calculated as the selling price per unit minus the variable cost per unit. This metric is crucial in decision-making processes such as shut-down decisions and production line closures. The contribution margin is used to cover fixed costs and generate profit.,6\n255,\"\"\"FIXED COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Fixed Costs\"\" are expenses that do not change with the level of production or sales. These costs remain constant regardless of the business activity level and include items such as rent, salaries, heat and power costs, fixed machine costs, depreciation, and insurance costs. While fixed costs are generally irrelevant to decision-making unless there is an incremental step in the fixed cost, they can be considered in decision-making when they can be avoided or reduced as a result of the decision.\",7\n1643,\"\"\"DISPLAY SCREENS\"\"\",\"\"\"Display screens are another component produced by Robber Co, with an annual production of 80,000 units. The production involves direct materials, direct labour, heat and power costs, machine costs, and depreciation and insurance costs.\"\"\",6\n1646,\"\"\"KEYPADS\"\"\",,6\n454,\"\"\"UNIT CONTRIBUTION\"\"\",\"\"\"Unit contribution\"\" is calculated as the selling price per unit minus the variable cost per unit. It is used to determine the breakeven point and target profit. The unit contribution represents the amount each unit contributes to covering fixed costs and generating profit.\",5\n1645,\"\"\"LABOUR HOURS\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour hours\"\" refer to the total number of hours worked by employees and are a critical factor in the production process. Specifically, for Robber Co, labour hours are required to produce keypads and display screens. It takes 0.5 labour hours to produce a keypad and 0.75 labour hours to produce a display screen. There is a total labour hour restriction of 100,000 hours, which serves as a limiting factor in production, particularly noted for month 2.\",4\n469,\"\"\"TARGET PROFIT CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Total contribution/Unit contribution = $380,000/40 = 9,500 units. Total revenue required: 9,500 \u00d7 $129 = $1,225,500\"\"\",3\n384,\"\"\"DEPRECIATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Depreciation is a method of allocating the cost of a tangible asset over its useful life. It is not a 